06976nam a22008535i 9780774860673DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2019304784  a97807748606737 a10.59962/97807748606732doi  a(DE-B1597)662134  a(OCoLC)1104821875  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aF1089.7.E3bU56 2019 4aF1089.7.E3bU56 2019 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a325/.25407109041223  aNP 60402rvk0(DE-625)rvk/127993:00aUnmooring the Komagata Maru :bCharting Colonial Trajectories /ced. by Renisa Mawani, Rita Dhamoon, Davina Bhandar, Satwinder Kaur Bains. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b6 b&w photos, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tChronology of Events -- tIntroduction -- tThe Politics of Anticolonial Resistance in the Journey of the Komagata Maru -- tRight to the Empire? -- tThe Last Stretch of the Journey -- tThe Resistance of Indian Migrants -- tMigration Regimes in Colonial Contexts -- tThe Komagata Maru as Event -- tBorders, Boats, and Brown Bodies -- tTemporary Arrivals -- tColonial Temporalities of Memory and Cultural Production -- tThe Komagata Maru Incident as Described in Two Japanese Works -- t(Mis)Representing the Komagata Maru in Indian Print Cultures -- tThe Time and Sound of the Nautical Border -- tDisrupting Colonial Formations of Nation -- tWhen Home and Harem Collide -- tThe Komagata Maru Recontextualized -- tPast Wrongs and a New National Imaginary -- tThe Politics of Empire -- tPoems -- tHistorical Figures Cited in the Chapters -- tBC Government Apology, May 23, 2008 -- tCanadian Government Apology, May 18, 2016 -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1914, the SS Komagata Maru crossed oceans and jurisdictions to arrive at the west coast of Canada. Canadian officials, calling on legislative acts designed to limit the immigration of Indians, detained the ship for two months in Vancouver Harbour. Most of the 376 passengers were then forcibly returned to India. Unmooring the Komagata Maru challenges conventional Canadian historical accounts by drawing from multiple disciplines and fields to consider the international and colonial dimensions of the voyage. By situating the history of South Asians in Canada in a global-imperial context, this volume emphasizes the ways in which the Komagata Maru incident is related to issues of colonialism more generally. The contributors offer a critical reading of Canadian multiculturalism through past events and their commemoration. Ultimately, they caution against narratives that present the ship’s journey as a dark moment in the history of a redeemed nation. Unmooring the Komagata Maru demonstrates that, a hundred years later, the voyage of the Komagata Maru has yet to reach its conclusion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEast IndianszBritish ColumbiazVancouverxHistoryy20th century. 0aImperialismxSocial aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aBains, Satwinder Kaur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBains, Satwinder Kaur, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBhandar, Davina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhandar, Davina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChattopadhyay, Suchetana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDhamoon, Rita Kaur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDhamoon, Rita, eeditor.4edt